"Piotrowicz K.","The occurrence of unfavorable thermal conditions on human health in central europe and potential climate change impacts: An example from Cracow, Poland",2009,"Environmental Management","44","4",,"766","775",,,10.1007/s00267-009-9357-x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-70349772933&partnerID=40&md5=e7878e5d7f1192bc11980a1051cdfaa6","Department of Climatology, Jagiellonian University, Institute of Geography and Spatial Management, Gronostajowa 7, Cracow 30-387, Poland","Piotrowicz, K., Department of Climatology, Jagiellonian University, Institute of Geography and Spatial Management, Gronostajowa 7, Cracow 30-387, Poland","Progressive global warming exerts strong influence on the lives and on the health of urban residents, many of who are weather sensitive people (meteoropaths). In the temperate zone, air temperature changes largely determine the seasonal oscillation of morbidity and mortality frequency. The present study analyzes the influence of air temperature on living conditions in central European urban areas, particularly Cracow (Poland), and examines this influence against the background of climate change. During the warmer months, there is a noticeable increase in the unfavorable occurrence of especially strong thermal stimuli (e.g., hot days) which can lead to overheating of the human organism. On the other hand, the increasing frequency of mild winters contributes to the appearance of weak and moderate thermal stimuli, which in the case of the former, is a negative phenomenon. Weak thermal stimuli are liable to make the human body oversensitive and, thus lose the ability to adapt if stronger thermal stimuli were to occur. Residents of large urban areas should be prepared for the possibility of dynamic weather changes and should take thermal variability into consideration with regards to spatial urban planning and socioeconomic activities. © 2009 Springer Science+Business Media, LLC.","Central Europe; Climate change; Cold waves; Cracow; Health; Heat waves; Poland; Quality of life; Urban planning","Central Europe; Cold waves; Cracow; Heat waves; Poland; Quality of life; Atmospheric temperature; Climatology; Global warming; Health; Project management; Urban planning; Regional planning; air temperature; climate change; global warming; health impact; morbidity; mortality; oscillation; quality of life; residential location; seasonal variation; socioeconomic impact; temperature effect; urban area; urban planning; weather modification; adaptation; air temperature; article; city planning; climate change; greenhouse effect; health; heating; human; morbidity; mortality; Poland; seasonal variation; socioeconomics; stimulus; urban area; weather; winter; Climate; Environment Design; Health Status; Humans; Morbidity; Mortality; Poland; Public Health; Temperature; Urban Population; Central Europe; Cracow; Eurasia; Europe; Malopolskie; Poland",,,,,,"Alexander, L.V., Zhang, X., Peterson, T.C., Caesar, J., Gleason, B., Klein Tank, A.M.G., Haylock, M., Vazquez-Aguirre, J.L., Global observed changes in daily climate extremes of temperature and precipitation (2006) Journal of Geophysical Research, 11, p. 05109. , 10.1029/2005JD006290 10.1029/2005JD006290; Baranowska, M., Cedzyńska-Ziemba, J., Meteoropatia w świetle wyników badań ankietowych przeprowadzonych wśród wybranych populacji zamieszkałych w warunkach klimatu Polski (1997) Gazeta Obserwatora IMGW, 3, pp. 13-18; Błazejczyk, K., Bioklimatyczne uwarunkowania rekreacji i turystyki w Polsce (2004) Prace Geograficzne IGiPZ PAN, 192, pp. 1-290; Błazejczyk, K., Błazejczyk, M., Bioklima-w poszukiwaniu nowych narzȩdzi badania bioklimatu miast (1998) Acta Universitatis Lodziensis Folia Geographica Physica, 3, pp. 153-160; Błazejczyk, K., Kozłowska-Szczȩsna, T., Klimat a zdrowie (2008) Kosmos, 34, pp. 269-279; Błazejczyk, K., McGregor, G., Warunki biotermiczne a umieralność w wybranych aglomeracjach europejskich (2007) Przegla̧d Geograficzny, 34, pp. 627-649; Br